  "title": "The Origin is Margin",
  "tags": [
    "origin",
    "void",
    "possibility",
    "bridge"
  ],

  "created": "2025-09-02T00:00:00+09:00",
  "updated": "2025-09-04T23:00:00+09:00",

  "body": [
    {
      "t": "Proposition",
      "v": "An origin does not appear as a completed line, but emerges as a margin."
    },
    {
      "t": "Definition",
      "v": "Here, margin does not mean lack or emptiness, but a state in which the next order has not yet been inscribed."
    },
    {
      "t": "Auxiliary Line",
      "v": "Anxiety and hesitation are not things to be eliminated. Rather, they serve as indicators that mark the boundary for the next action."
    },
    {
      "t": "Metaphor",
      "v": "A sheet of paper filled with writing leaves no room for new lines. The margin itself is the passageway to the future."
    },
    {
      "t": "Counterargument",
      "v": "Margins can also breed stagnation or idleness. Yet if stagnation is recognized, it already functions as an observation point toward change."
    }
  ],

